          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Divide cost incurred to date by the total estimated cost of the contract, then apply that percentage to the contract value. Costs of Rs 6 crore against an estimated Rs 10 crore give 60 per cent completion, so Rs 9 crore of a Rs 15 crore contract is recognised as revenue to date. Any expected loss is booked immediately in full."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between the percentage of completion method and the completed contract method?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The percentage of completion method recognises revenue and profit progressively as work is performed, while the completed contract method holds everything back until the contract finishes. Percentage of completion spreads profit across years and is required for construction contracts under AS 7. The completed contract method is no longer permitted for construction contracts in Indian financial statements."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is the percentage of completion method compulsory for tax in India?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes for most contractors. ICDS III on construction contracts requires the percentage of completion method for computing taxable income, and permits revenue recognition to be deferred only while completion stays below 25 per cent. Companies applying Ind AS 115 recognise revenue over time on a similar input measure, so book and tax profiles usually track each other."
          }
        }
